Per-customer perspective: Brad Hall is the most price-sensitive

Brad Hall's 4 same-day observations:Brad Hall's personal break point looks to be ~$0.30–$0.35. Below that he gives Denver the majority; above $0.45 he gives N Platte the majority. The aggregate signal from this customer alone implies you lose ~50% of his Denver volume between a $0.31 and $0.51 spread.

Recommended pricing posture :bulb:

• Safe zone: spread ≤ $0.20 — historically held 90%+ Denver share with low volatility.
• Watch zone: spread $0.20–$0.35 — Denver still gets most of the volume but starting to bleed to N Platte (esp. Brad Hall, Musket). Acceptable if Denver's incremental margin per gallon exceeds the lost-volume cost.
• Danger zone: spread  $0.40 — substitution kicks in hard. Realized 17 days at this level over the window and Denver took only 44.6% share. Pricing here only makes sense if you actively want the volume to move to N Platte (e.g., capacity constraints at Denver).

Caveats :warning:

• Asymmetric data: only 3 of 46 dual days had Denver cheaper than N Platte. The curve above is only well-anchored for positive spreads (Denver costing more). I can't tell you with confidence what happens if you flip the sign — there's almost no precedent in the window.
• Sample size in the danger zone: the $0.40+ band's average is dragged down by May 2–May 8, when N Platte ran a sustained 5-day high-volume burst. If that was driven by a specific event (large customer order, supply constraint at a competitor terminal, etc.) rather than pure price response, the true substitution slope may be gentler than $0.40 → 45% suggests.
• Behavioral switching is concentrated: the elasticity above is largely Brad Hall + Musket + a handful of Maverik allocations. If those two customers' purchasing patterns change (volume, contract terms, ownership), the curve shifts.
• N Platte capacity: N Platte ran ~21% of combined volume and had 35 zero-lift days. Even with a $0.50+ spread, NPL may not be able to absorb a large Denver-share migration if customers don't already have logistics set up there.

Bottom line: hold the Denver-vs-N Platte spread at ≤ $0.25/gal to preserve ~90% share. Anything you charge above $0.25 should be a deliberate trade of share for margin, and above $0.40 you should expect to lose roughly half the substitutable volume to N Platte.

